SIMPLE: sally
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sally
<hw>Sal"ly</hw> <pr>(s⟦acr⟧l"l⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Sallied</conjf>
<pr>(-l⟦icr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sallying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>saillir</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>salire</ets> to leap, spring, akin to Gr. <grk>"a`llesqai</grk>;
cf. Skr. <ets>s⟦rsdot⟧</ets> to go, to flow. Cf. <er>Salient</er>,
<er>Assail</er>, <er>Assault</er>, <er>Exult</er>, <er>Insult</er>,
<er>Saltation</er>, <er>Saltire</er>.]</ety> <def>To leap or rush out;
to burst forth; to issue suddenly; as a body of troops from a fortified
place to attack besiegers; to make a sally.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They break the truce, and <qex>sally</qex> out by night.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The foe retires, -- she heads the <qex>sallying</qex> host.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sally</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sally
<hw>Sal"ly</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Sallies</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>saillie</ets>, fr. <ets>saillir</ets>.
See <ets>Sally</ets>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A leaping
forth; a darting; a spring.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A rushing or bursting forth; a quick issue; a sudden
eruption; specifically, an issuing of troops from a place besieged to
attack the besiegers; a sortie.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sallies</qex> were made by the Spaniards, but they were
beaten in with loss.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An excursion from the usual track; range;
digression; deviation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every one shall know a country better that makes often
<qex>sallies</qex> into it, and traverses it up and down, than he that .
. . goes still round in the same track.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A flight of fancy, liveliness, wit, or the like; a
flashing forth of a quick and active mind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The unaffected mirth with which she enjoyed his
<qex>sallies</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Transgression of the limits of soberness or
steadiness; act of levity; wild gayety; frolic; escapade.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The excursion was esteemed but a <qex>sally</qex> of youth.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sally port</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Fort.)</fld>
<cd>A postern gate, or a passage underground, from the inner to the
outer works, to afford free egress for troops in a sortie</cd>.
<sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Naval)</fld> <cd>A large port on each quarter of a
fireship, for the escape of the men into boats when the train is fired;
a large port in an old-fashioned three-decker or a large modern
ironclad.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sally Lunn</ent>⟦br⟧
